  <entry>
    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Fix rake new_post['title'] and Zsh]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.benjaminguillet.com/blog/2013/06/24/fix-rake-new-post-title-and-zsh/"/>
    <updated>2013-06-24T16:09:00-07:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.benjaminguillet.com/blog/2013/06/24/fix-rake-new-post-title-and-zsh</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>There is a bug with Zsh and the Octopress rake new_post command.</p>

<p>Everytime you try to create a new post using this command, you get this:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>rake new_post<span class="o">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;My new post&quot;</span><span class="o">]</span>
</span><span class='line'>zsh: no matches found: new_post<span class="o">[</span>My new post<span class="o">]</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>The only workaround so far is:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>rake new_post<span class="se">\[</span><span class="s2">&quot;My new post&quot;</span><span class="se">\]</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>

]]></content>
  </entry>
  
  <entry>
    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Testing your local variables in a Rails view]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.benjaminguillet.com/blog/2013/06/24/testing-your-local-variables-in-a-rails-view/"/>
    <updated>2013-06-24T16:01:00-07:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.benjaminguillet.com/blog/2013/06/24/testing-your-local-variables-in-a-rails-view</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Let&#8217;s say you want to add a class to HTML tag, but not all the time.</p>

<p>You can check if the local variable is set in a view like this:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='haml'><span class='line'><span class="nc">.mobile-widget</span><span class="p">{</span> <span class="ss">:class</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">defined?</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">klass</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">?</span> <span class="n">klass</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="kp">nil</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="s1">&#39;data-view&#39;</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="s1">&#39;MobileWidget&#39;</span> <span class="p">}</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>But there is a much better way. Simply do this:</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='haml'><span class='line'><span class="nc">.mobile-widget</span><span class="p">{</span> <span class="ss">:class</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="n">local_assigns</span><span class="o">[</span><span class="ss">:klass</span><span class="o">]</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;data-view&#39;</span> <span class="o">=&gt;</span> <span class="s1">&#39;MobileWidget&#39;</span> <span class="p">}</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>

]]></content>
